[The 1st 3 paragraphs below are adapted from the FDA's Bad Bug Book
http://www.fda.gov/Food/FoodSafety/FoodborneIllness/FoodborneIllnessFoodbornePathogensNaturalToxins/BadBugBook/ucm070040.htm:

Because of the degree of abdominal pain, yersiniosis has been
misdiagnosed as Crohn's disease as well as appendicitis. Diagnosis of
yersiniosis begins with isolation of the organism from the feces or
blood and sometimes at the time of appendectomy. Confirmation occurs
with the isolation, as well as biochemical and serological
identification, of _Y. enterocolitica_ from both the human host and
the ingested foodstuff. Diarrhea is reported to occur in about 80
percent of cases; abdominal pain and fever are the most reliable
symptoms. Because of the difficulties in isolating yersiniae from
feces, several countries rely on serology.
_Y. enterocolitica_ can be found in meats (pork, beef, lamb, etc.),
oysters, fish, and raw (not usually pasteurized) milk. The exact cause
of the food contamination is unknown. However, the prevalence of this
organism in the soil and water and in animals such as beavers, pigs,
and squirrels, offers ample opportunities for it to enter our food
supply. Poor sanitation and improper sterilization techniques by food
handlers, including improper storage, cannot be overlooked as
contributing to contamination.

The major "complication" is the performance of unnecessary
appendectomies, since one of the main symptoms of infections is
abdominal pain of the lower right quadrant. Yersiniosis may also be
associated with reactive arthritis, which may occur even in the
absence of obvious symptoms. The frequency of such post-enteritis
arthritic conditions is about 2-3 percent.

ProMED has periodically posted on human infections associated with the
ingestion of "raw" unpasteurized milk. Pasteurization
(http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pasteurization) is a process of
heating a food, usually liquid, to a specific temperature for a
definite length of time, and then cooling it immediately.
Pasteurization, unlike sterilization, is not intended to kill all
micro-organisms in the food. Instead pasteurization aims to reduce the
number of viable pathogens so they are unlikely to cause disease
(assuming the pasteurized product is stored as indicated and consumed
before its expiration date). Although known in China and Japan, the
modern version was created by Louis Pasteur, after whom it is named,
conceived as a way of preventing wine and beer from souring.

It is not the case, however, that pasteurized milk or milk products
are never able to transmit infection. In response to a cluster of
appendectomies in an area of New York State in the fall of 1976,
investigators found that an epidemic of _Y. enterocolitica_ had
occurred and that it was associated with the drinking of school-bought
chocolate milk (1). The pasteurization technique in the dairy was
found to be satisfactory and the investigation suggested that the
organism was introduced at the dairy during mixing by hand of
chocolate syrup and pasteurized milk, a post-pasteurization
contamination. An huge outbreak of _Salmonella_ Enteritidis in the USA
occurred in 1994 when ice cream pre-mix, already pasteurized, was
transported by tanker trailers that had just carried non-pasteurized
eggs (2) and an estimated 224 000 infections occurred.

Post-pasteurization contamination of milk is thought to underly most
of these outbreaks associated with pasteurized milk, although the
mechanism of contamination may not be elucidated. Such outbreaks
include more than 16 000 culture-confirmed cases of _Salmonella_
Typhimurium in Illinois reported in 1987 (3), a multistate outbreak of
_Y. enterocolitica in 1982 (4), as well an outbreaks of listeriosis in
Massachusetts in 1983 (5). The listeriosis outbreak, however, was one
in which the investigators raised questions about the ability of
pasteurization to eradicate a large inoculum of certain organisms from
raw milk.

The persistence of small numbers of pathogenic organisms may not be
relevant since the milk is kept at refrigerator temperatures for most
organisms, but for _L. monocytogenes_ and _Y. enterocolitica_ this may
not be the case. Certain organisms like these can be referred to as
psychrotrophs, defined as bacteria that may grow at 7 degrees C [44.6
degrees F] or below, irrespective of their optimal temperature for
growth (6). These organisms, if remaining at some number after
pasteurization or inoculated after pasteurization, can then replicate
in the refrigerated milk.

Although the risk from pasteurized milk is quite small, there is some.
Some, if not most, of this risk is from post-pasteurization
contamination but not all. Be that as it may, unpasteurized milk has a
much higher risk.

References:
1. Black RE, Jackson RJ, Tsai T, et al: Epidemic _Yersinia
enterocolitica_ infection due to contaminated chocolate milk. N Engl J
Med 1978;298: 76-79.
2. Hennessy TW, Hedberg CW, Slutsker L, et al: A national outbreak of
_Salmonella_ Enteritidis infections from ice cream. N Engl J Med
1996;334: 1281-1286.
3. Ryan CA, Nickels MK, Hargrett-Bean NT, et al: Massive outbreak of
antimicrobial-resistant salmonellosis traced to pasteurized milk. JAMA
1987;258: 3269-3274.
4. Tacket CO, Narain JP, Sattin R, et al: A multistate outbreak of
infections caused by _Yersinia enterocolitica_ transmitted by
pasteurized milk. JAMA 1984;251: 483-486.
5. Fleming DW, Cochi SL, MacDonald KL, et al: Pasteurized milk as a
vehicle of infection in an outbreak of listeriosis. N Engl J Med
1985;312: 404-407.
6. Champagne CP, Laing RR, Roy R, Matu AA: Psychotrophs in dairy
products: their effects and their control. Crit Rev Food Sci Nutrit
1994;34: 1-30.]
